  <section class="section section-tinted">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header"><div class="eyebrow">09 &middot; Six forces shaping Florida physical therapy</div><h2>How Florida physical therapy practice operates in 2026.</h2><p>FL physical therapy at intersection of DPT doctorate mandate + direct access expansion + chain consolidation + retirement orthopedic demand + sports medicine subspecialty growth + FL no-state-income-tax advantage.</p></div>
      <h3>Force 1 &mdash; DPT doctorate mandate</h3>
      <p>Entry-level DPT required since 2016 per CAPTE mandate. Pre-2016 MPT clinicians grandfathered. 3-year doctoral program at CAPTE-accredited institutions + FSBPT NPTE licensure exam. Substantial educational investment supporting practice positioning + practice authority advocacy + scope expansion arguments. ~280 CAPTE-accredited DPT programs nationwide graduating ~12,000 DPTs annually.</p>
      <h3>Force 2 &mdash; Direct access expansion</h3>
      <p>Florida direct access (no physician referral required for evaluation + initial treatment) expanded 2018 supporting PT practice autonomy. ~30-day initial treatment window without referral. Substantial scope expansion supporting private practice growth + patient access + practice ownership opportunity + reduced physician gatekeeper dependency.</p>
      <h3>Force 3 &mdash; Chain consolidation pathway</h3>
      <p>Outpatient clinic chain consolidation 2015-2026 with PE-backed platforms (Select Medical, Athletico, US Physical Therapy, Ivy Rehab, ATI Physical Therapy, Pivot) acquiring private practices at 5-8× EBITDA. Sale + earnout + equity rollover + post-acquisition employment pathway. Substantial wealth opportunity for senior practice owners. Multi-clinic owners particularly well-positioned for premium acquisition multiples.</p>
      <h3>Force 4 &mdash; FL retirement orthopedic demand</h3>
      <p>Florida retirement population substantial PT demand: orthopedic rehab (joint replacement + spine + sports injury) + geriatric rehab (fall prevention + balance + functional mobility) + neurologic rehab (stroke + Parkinson&rsquo;s + MS) + cardiac rehab. Medicare patient concentration substantial. Driving substantial DPT demand across all categories particularly hospital-employed + private practice.</p>
      <h3>Force 5 &mdash; Sports medicine subspecialty growth</h3>
      <p>Sports medicine PT subspecialty substantial growth with athletic + recreational sports injury patient base. FL professional sports teams + collegiate + high school athletic team consulting. Running + endurance sports market expansion. ABPTS SCS subspecialty certification supporting differentiation. Pediatric + neurologic subspecialty also growing supporting specialty practice premium.</p>
      <h3>Force 6 &mdash; FL no-state-income-tax DPT concentration</h3>
      <p>FL no state income tax substantial DPT income preservation. Senior practice owner $250K-$400K+: California (13.3%) saves $33K-$53K+; New York (10.9%) saves $27K-$44K+ annually relocating to Florida. Multi-million lifetime tax preservation driving substantial DPT relocations 2020-2026 from high-tax states.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

